        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1979-02-02T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1979-02-02T00:00:00-05:00" n="122"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d122">
                <head>122. Memorandum From the President’s Assistant for National Security Affairs
                        (<persName corresp="#p_BZ_1">Brzezinski</persName>) to President <persName
                        corresp="#p_CJE_1">Carter</persName>
                    <note n="1" type="source" xml:id="d122fn1">Source: Carter Library, National
                        Security Affairs, Brzezinski Material, President’s Daily <gloss
                            target="#t_CIA_1">CIA</gloss> Brief File, Box 17, 2/1/79–2/7/79. Top
                        Secret; Sensitive. Printed from an uninitialed copy. <persName
                            corresp="#p_CH_1">Carter</persName> initialed at the top of the
                        memorandum.</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>Washington</placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian"
                            when="1979-02-02">February 2, 1979</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <list type="subject">
                    <head>SUBJECT</head>
                    <item>Daily Report (U)</item>
                </list>
                <p>[Omitted here is material unrelated to India.]</p>
                <p>
                    <hi rend="italic">Nuclear Policy Problems in India</hi>: Most middle-level
                    Indian nuclear scientists disagree with the government’s stand against signing
                    the Non-Proliferation Treaty and accepting full safeguards on Indian nuclear
                    facilities, according to a clandestine source. The scientists are said to
                    believe that these steps are necessary to acquire the foreign assistance that is
                    essential to their work and ultimately to their careers. (S)</p>
                <p>Research into gas centrifuge enrichment reportedly is proceeding on such a small
                    scale and with so little direction that India may be dependent for many years on
                    the U.S. supply of enriched uranium for the Tarapur power reactors. New Delhi’s
                    refusal to accept U.S. conditions on safeguards could eventually force the
                    Tarapur station to close. (S)</p>
                <p>[Omitted here is material unrelated to India.]</p>
            </div>
